		<header>
			
			<h1>SADC trade policy: Non-tariff barriers are focus of discussion in Southern and Eastern Africa</h1>

			
			<h4>
												02 May 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>At the SADC Ministerial meeting in Windhoek on 4 March 2011, ‘serious concern’ was expressed at the impact of non-tariff barriers on intra-regional trade. Examples cited in media reports included vitamin-A fortification requirements for sugar imports into Zambia and minimum tonnage requirements for the export of fresh strawberries from Zambia to Zimbabwe. Press reports argued that all over the region, ‘sensitive industries’ like the dairy sector were being protected by ‘banning imports from neighbours’.</p><p>Namibian officials are reported to have complained that ‘some members of the SADC FTA are not coming forward and don’t participate in the [SADC trade] protocol’, and as such ‘they are not working towards regional integration’. Currently Angola, the DRC and Seychelles have yet to join in the SADC FTA liberalisation process.</p><p>Lack of progress towards a SACU customs union, despite nominal commitments, has been linked in the press to the current disputes within the SACU on the central issues of revenue sharing. While SADC ministers reportedly saw ‘no contradiction between working towards a customs union and expanding the free trade area’, for South Africa ‘the tripartite FTA has moved to the front of the agenda’. Significantly, it has been pointed out that the implementation challenges currently faced under the SADC FTA will be replicated within any ‘grand tripartite FTA’.</p><p>The discussion on non-tariff barriers is wide ranging, including as it does the need to develop transport and other infrastructure essential to the promotion of trade. In this context, the South African authorities are placing considerable emphasis on the ‘North-South Corridor, which will link central Africa to the port of Durban, via Zambia and the Trans-Cunene Corridor, which will link the DRC with South Africa through Angola and Namibia’. These infrastructure initiatives are seen as complementary to the launch of the grand tripartite free-trade area. The absence of harmonised road haulage standards is also seen as major problem. South Africa’s trade and industry minister has further identified a need for standards harmonisation in order to boost regional exports to the South African market.</p><p>Press reports indicate that the high-level expert group agreed at the SADC summit of August 2010 ‘has now been appointed to consolidate and refine technical work’ in order to establish ‘[a] common understanding on parameters, benchmarks, timelines’ and implementation modalities for both the deepening of existing free-trade arrangements and the eventual establishment of a customs union.</p><p>Meanwhile, despite a 49% increase in EAC intra-regional trade since the launch of the EAC customs union, press reports indicate that ‘the lack of a harmonised trade policy in the East African Community (EAC) is hampering the ability of the region to consolidate the gains made under the Customs Union.’ While the Common Market Protocol, which provides for free movement of goods, has been in force since July 2010, this is not yet being successfully applied, largely due to a failure of member states to ‘fully [align] their national legal and regulatory laws and policies’ with the new comprehensive trade and economic integration policy commitments.</p>
		
		
