				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Non-tariff barriers to trade can have a particularly disruptive effect on regional trade in fresh agricultural products. This requires a progressive harmonisation of product standards in order to create a single internal market for fresh agricultural products, thereby gaining economies of scale in production. However in the SADC context this needs to be reconciled with national aspirations to develop local production for local markets, in a context where the dominance of South African-based companies can create serious distortions in the functioning of value chains. While initiatives in the Namibian horticultural sector are illustrative of the types of policy tool that can be used to strengthen the functioning of value chains, at minimum additional cost to consumers and with minor distortion of regional trade, there are important policy implications that need to be discussed and integrated into the regional policy elaboration.</p><p>Health-related standards can also become non-tariff barriers to trade when these are not harmonised across the region (e.g. the requirement to include vitamin supplements in basic foodstuffs placed for sale on national markets). Harmonisation of standards in this area, however, requires a deepening and extension of inter-governmental dialogue to reach beyond trade and agricultural ministries to public health departments. Technical and financial support may well be required to facilitate this process.</p><p>Overall, getting to grips with the non-tariff barriers to trade in food and agricultural products can require a lot of detailed technical work before an effective regional framework can be set in place. At many levels the EC and EU member states are involved in extending support in these areas. Equally the EU is actively involved in addressing a range of ‘hardware’ barriers to trade, for example the development of transport infrastructure along the North-South Transport Corridor. It is at this technical and financial level where the EU can make the greatest contribution to the progressive removal of non-tariff barriers to trade in southern Africa, for it is at the design and implementation level (rather than the policy commitment level) where the greatest challenges are faced.</p>
		</div>
		
